Serious Security Flaws in Mediaroom.com
text:
I have recently been searching the internet for different efficiencies in security have have encountered a very worrying situation.

While browsing on the site tripadvisor.com, after navigating to their page entitled "US Press Center | TripAdvisor" I had noticed a script was attempting to load that was blocked by my browser's Adblock. Although I am very certain of what's below, I would highly suggest you were to go ahead with independent enquiries to validate my findings -- Findings which are extremely worrying.

The script being loaded is named "moatframe.js", this file is loaded from the following URL; https://z.moatads.com/addthismoatframe568911941483/moatframe.js. There are conflicting results after searching this particular filename, but as mentioned I have de-obfuscating the code.

Side note: After navigating to moatads.com, there was previously an A record, which would return to a redirect to a large networking company (which to the best of my knowledge was CISCO). However, there is a possibility that an individual thread actor would be able to hide behind the name of a company as large as CISCO.

After decompiling the script, we found that the code calls a system API call to a function named "MSFAPI". This script is in essence calling the Metasploit Framework API.

This particular framework allows a remote javascript shell to be created, which wouldn't be an issue if it weren't for a venerability it can potentially target on Edge products running on Microsoft.

With this particular framework we were able to find a gitlab server that seems highly related containing code that can essentially open a local shell on Microsoft Windows 10. This exploit originally targeted routers, but is no longer online, the code was previously hosted at the domain http://git.hunter-ht.cn/.

This alone would allow for local files to be pulled from the server and modified. Along with a privilege escalation attack, a key logger, RAT or something similar may be installed on the chosen computer merely by accessing the webpage.

As mentioned, please double check my findings, as someone who uses the internet I strongly hope I am wrong.

Please let me know your own findings.

Owen.

Show HN: Tandem – An Engine for Secure Multi-Party Computation (Written in Rust)
text:
Tandem is a cryptographic engine for executing programs using Secure Multi-Party Computation (MPC), which allows 2 parties to compute a function without revealing their private inputs. The classic example from cryptography is the millionaires' problem, where two millionaires compute who is richer without revealing their wealth to each other.

MPC has in the past been mostly confined to academia, but thanks to some recent papers has finally become fast enough for practical applications. Tandem uses Garbled Circuits, encrypted circuits consisting of boolean gates. While there have been other implementations based on these ideas, Tandem tries to provide a much better user experience than previous attempts. For example, the Tandem repo includes a server, a command line client and client libs for wasm and native architectures. To make it easier to run practical applications, programs can be written in Garble, a custom Rust-like programming language that compiles to Garbled Circuits.

(The most practical application to date using Tandem is "Encryptle", a Wordle clone that runs entirely over MPC. Depending on latency, a client/server exchange takes about 400ms, which makes the UX very similar to the real Wordle, with the twist that the server cannot see the guess in plain text and the browser cannot see the solution in plain text. Instead, guess and solution are kept private and compared using MPC.)

Ask HN: What do you wish you knew before you developed your first video game?
text:
I'm going to be taking some time off from work here at the end of the year to pursue some creative software development.

Although I have almost 15 years of industry experience I've never built a game. Up until about six months ago, I didn't think I was /that/ type of software developer, but now, here I am, interest piqued, reading up on all sorts of technology stacks and having my mind blown by the size of the knowledge space. I am especially excited to try and express logic using an ECS/DOTS approach!

I know I am building for desktop web. Leaning towards Rust + WebGPU and hoping to time an MVP around WebGPU general availability. I know I shouldn't be in this space for the money. I know to expect game programming to be significantly more challenging than whatever my intuition believes and that I should continually and aggressively prune away at scope creep. I know there's a LOT of math and that performance is frequently an issue.

What are some joys, or challenges, you unexpectedly encountered when developing your first game which you wish you'd known before breaking ground?
